Restoring the very American ideal that labor rights are also human rights
Congressmen Keith Ellison and John Lewis have proposed a bill to protect union organizing as a civil right.
"The way the unions work, jobs work for the middle class," says Ellison, a Democratic senator from Minnesota who is co-chair of the Congressional Committee.
That is why I am so proud to introduce, together with john lewis' model of intermittent rights, a law empowering employees.
This groundbreaking legislation will give workers the same legal options to prevent discrimination in trade union organizing as other forms of discrimination - and stop anti-union forces
Adjusting the Labour Relations Act to allow all employees facing discrimination if they want to join a union to sue in civil court - and to sue for compensation or damages - is the right and necessary initiative.
But it is certainly not a radical initiative - at least not by American standards.
The best way to understand what Ellison, Lewis, and other proponents are proposing in the bill is to reconnect with the American ideal.
Despite the union fights that have taken place in recent years - in Wisconsin, Michigan, and other states - Americans once encouraged countries around the world to embrace, expand, and respect labor rights.
There was a time, and millions of Americans still remember it, when the country in the same breath promoted democracy, freedom of speech, freedom of the press, and the right to assemble.
When the United States occupied Japan after World War II, General Douglas MacArthur and his advisers encouraged the country to adopt a constitution designed to ensure that hideki toya's military autocracies were replaced by democracy.
Convinced that employees and their unions played a role in shaping the new Japan, they included language in them and openly acknowledged that "the right of employees to gather, collectively negotiate, and act is guaranteed."
When the United States occupied Germany after World War II, General Dwight David Eisenhower and his advisers encouraged the Germans to create a constitution to ensure that Adolf Hitler's fascism was replaced by a strong democracy.
Aware that employees would need to organize and promote themselves in the new nation, the Germans included a clause that openly states: "The right to form associations that secure and improve working and economic conditions will be guaranteed to every individual and to every profession or profession.
Arrangements restricting or seeking to damage this right will be revoked. Measures to fulfil such a purpose are illegal.
When former First Lady Eleanor Roosevelt chaired the International Commission on Human Rights, which proposed the Universal Declaration of Human Rights, which was adopted by the United Nations as a global treaty in 1948, the plaintiffs and Roosevelt included a guarantee that "everyone has the right to form and enter into trade unions in order to protect their interests."
For generations, Americans have accepted the basic premisus that labor rights are human rights.
When the country advised other countries on how to create a civil and democratic society, Americans explained that the right to form labor unions - and their participation in collective bargaining with companies and government agencies as an equal partner - must be protected.
Now that these rights are being challenged in America, it is absolutely necessary to return to the American ideal that working people must have the right to organize and promote themselves in a free and open society.
As the Reverend Martin Luther King Jr. said 50 years ago:
History is a great teacher.
Today, everyone knows that the unions have not diminished the strength of the nation, but expanded it.
They have raised the standard of living of millions of people, created a market for industry, and raised production to unsued levels.
Those who challenge unions forget these simple truths, but history remembers them.
History does not forget, and we should not.
Formal recognition of labour rights as human rights - and extending civil rights protections to prevent discrimination in the organisation of trade unions - is long overdue.
Keith Ellison and John Lewis are restoring the ideals that lifted America up and made it a true promise of democracy.
Judge temporarily blocks law that could close all louisiana abortion clinics
A federal judge on Sunday temporarily blocked a Louisiana law that advocates say would likely shut down all five abortion clinics in the state.
The ordinance, enacing Louisiana Governor Bobby Jindal's signature in June, due to take effect on September 1, would require abortion doctors to have the right to receive a patient at a hospital within 30 miles of performing their practice.
The judge's order means that doctors can temporarily continue to perform legal abortions and must obtain such permission in the meantime.
"The proposing party will be able to legally operate and obtain a permit in the meantime," the order from federal Judge John deGravelles states.
The hearing will be scheduled within a month so that the judge can issue a more permanent order regarding the law.
Abortion rights activists welcomed the resolution, the latest in a series of similar measures, and said it would give doctors more time to obtain a permit.
"Today's decision ensures that women in Louisiana are safe from a tricky law that is intended to deprive them of their health and their rights," said Nancy Northup, president and CEO of the Center for Reproductive Rights, which sued three of the five clinics to block the law.
It was not immediately clear whether the decision also applies to doctors from two clinics that were not among the plaintiffs, and they are also seeking permission.
Louisiana is among 11 states that have passed similar laws, with courts in Alabama and Mississippi declareing such measures unconstitutional.
Key parts of a Texas law that would have closed most of the state's remaining clinics were blocked by a federal judge Friday.
Women's abortion rights campaigners, along with the Association of American Obstetricians and Gynecologists and the American Medical Association, argue that the need to have such a permit places medically non-medical requirements on doctors.
Opponents of abortion argue that the measures are aimed at protecting women's health, and some also welcomed the fact that the measures would close clinics.
The Center for Reproductive Rights said that in Louisiana, only one abortion doctor has a permit.
If all doctors in the state were forced to stop performing abortions, the doctor would also stop performing the procedure for fear of his safety, the group said.
In response, Louisiana authorities said they would not punish doctors who perform abortions while they wait for a rights application to be processed.
