Genetic disorders are often misdiagnosed
A woman from Britain describes how, after a misdiagnosis, she thought she was going to die for many years.
After being diagnosed with another disease, Karin Rodgers spent most of her adolescence under the notion that she had only a few years to live.
In fact, it was Charcot-Marie-Tooth syndrome (CMT) - a group of hereditary disorders that damage nerves outside the brain and spine.
The charity CMT UK said misdiagnosis is a common problem among people with CMT because very little is known about the disease.
Around 23,000 people in the UK are thought to suffer from CMT, which can manifest symptoms in the motor skills sector such as muscle weakness, clumsy walking and twisted toes.
In those affected, numbness or pain may also occur, this condition is incurable and progressive, which means that over time the symptoms get worse.
When Rodgers was 13, she thought she was suffering from Freidreich's ataxia (FA) - a condition that has a very poor prognosis.
She believed that by the time she celebrated her 18th birthday, she'd be wheelchair bound and dead by the time she was 30.
The mother-of-two, who is now 51, says: "As a child, I knew I couldn't do the same things as everyone else.
I fell every day and everything took me longer.
I could never roller skate or skateboard with other kids, and I was bullied at school because of the way I walked and ran."
When Rodgers was 13 and had several surgeries to clear her Achilles tendons and straighten her feet, she took advantage of her doctor's leave of the room and looked into her documentation, where she learned she was suffering from the FA.
"I felt guilty because I was snooping around, so I didn't tell anyone, but when I got home, I looked up information about the illness in the library and wrote to the FA Association," she says.
When they answered me, I was shocked, completely panicked.
I thought by the time I was 18, I'd end up in a wheelchair, and by the time I was 25, I'd be dead, and in the meantime, I'd gradually lose all my powers.
I was all alone, planning a funeral."
When she was 17, she realized that her walking ability had not deteriorated as much as she had anticipated, and asked her surgeon about it.
He just stood up, hugged her and said, "Sweetheart, I don't think you have the disease, or you'd be in a wheelchair by now.
I think it's going to be something much less life-threatening."
After undergoing several genetic tests, it was discovered that he had CMT.
