Companies in D.C., Maryland, and Vriginia paid more than $10 billion in state and local property taxes last year, an annual increase of 4.2% compared to $9.6 billion in 2012.
But the apparent increase in the value of real estate does not drive up state and local tax revenues so much in Maryland, where real estate taxes represent less than a fifth of corporate taxation.
For companies in Virginia and D.C., property taxes represent nearly half of state and local taxes.
